<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><a href="http://www.google.com/patents?vid=USPAT5004232" class="postlink">Google's page about this patent</a> says it was filed on October 13, 1989, and issued on April 2, 1991. This means it won't expire for a few more months.<br /></div>20 years is the maximum term, but if maintenance fees are not paid they can expire sooner. This specific patent appears to have expired in 1995 due to non-payment of maintenance fee; click the "INPADOC legal status" tab on the Espacenet page for the patent.<br /><br />Update: You can confirm that on the USPTO web site. Go <a href="https://ramps.uspto.gov/eram/patentMaintFees.do" class="postlink">here</a> and enter 5004232 for Patent Number, 07421164 for Application Number, then click "Get Bibliographic Data". The patent expired on 2 April 2005.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">BootGod wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />It's interesting that it says that, because the NINA-001 PCB doesn't use the MX8018, but instead uses a rather large 24-pin chip like seen here (chip U3).<br /><br />But now take a look at this one, which is even bigger, 28-pin, and has the very ROM-like part # of 23C1033.<br /><br />And finally, take a look at this one, what's sitting in spot U1!?<br /><br />I hope I still have that second cart, now I wanna pull that chip out and try reading it as if it was a ROM....<br /></div>Very interesting! So it looks like at least some carts have a combined ROM and CIC defeat chip. Looking at the board pics, NINA-001 REV. A has space for a 32-pin IC where the 24-pin chip is fitted. Have you traced the layout of the U3 pins on that board? If you dumped those carts, did the amount of data correspond with there being an additional ROM chip on the board?<br /><br />It does seem a bit strange though. For the Impossible Mission II with NINA-001 REV. A board, the 23C1033 part number (and chip size) suggests it's a 1Mbit ROM, which definitely doesn't tally with the game size.<br /><br />If the U3 chip <em>is</em> a ROM, the only thing I can think of (and it seems unlikely) is that AVE had a load of spare ROM/CIC-defeat chips, maybe from older titles that didn't sell well? But then, why wouldn't they just use a combined ROM/CIC-defeat for the main PRG ROM???<br /><br />-- M<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=316">mark_k</a> — Fri May 22, 2009 11:18 am</p><hr />
