<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-05-21T13:22:47-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-05-21T13:22:47-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5201&amp;p=47111#p47111</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5201&amp;p=47111#p47111"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Hold your horses]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5201&amp;p=47111#p47111"><![CDATA[
When the United States joined the World Trade Organization, it changed the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Term_of_patent_in_the_United_States" class="postlink">term of patent</a> as follows:<br /><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>Patents that expire prior to June 1995: 17 years after issue </li><li>Patents in force or pending as of June 1995: the longer of 17 years after issue or 20 years after filing </li><li>Patents applied for after June 1995: 20 years after filing </li><li>Patents reissued after reexamination: Same expiry date as original patent</li></ol><br /><a href="http://www.google.com/patents?vid=USPAT5004232" class="postlink">Google's page about this patent</a> says it was filed on October 13, 1989, and issued on April 2, 1991. This means it won't expire for a few more months.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu May 21, 2009 1:22 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
